<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="okr-setting">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>OKRs connect inspiring qualitative Objectives to quantitative Key Results (measurable outcomes, not tasks) within a fixed period. Set 3-5 per period at 70% confidence. Track weekly, score quarterly.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>okr</tag>
      <tag>goal-setting</tag>
      <tag>quarterly-planning</tag>
      <tag>key-results</tag>
      <tag>outcomes</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>OKR Setting</title>

    <summary>OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) connect inspiring qualitative goals to quantitative progress measures within a fixed period. The hard constraints: 3-5 Objectives per period, each with 3-5 Key Results; KRs must be measurable outcomes (not tasks or outputs); target confidence is 70%, not 100%. A six-step process covers drafting, validation, communication, and weekly tracking.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Goal-setting without structure produces goals that are either unmeasurable ("improve the product") or output-focused ("ship 5 features"). OKRs solve this by forcing separation of ambition (Objective) from evidence (Key Result), and by setting the 70% confidence bar—high enough to require real work, low enough to allow genuine stretch. Weekly check-ins prevent the "set and forget" failure mode.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new quarter or planning period.</item>
        <item>Team or product lacks shared measurable goals and every priority feels equal.</item>
        <item>Key Results exist but they're shipping tasks, not outcomes—need a rewrite.</item>
        <item>Post-retrospective realignment when previous goals missed.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fewer than 4 weeks of work horizon—overhead exceeds signal, use a sprint goal.</item>
        <item>Goals are externally mandated contractual deliverables—OKRs add no value over a contract.</item>
        <item>No baseline metrics available; KRs without baselines are fiction.</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF stage with zero users—measuring retention or NPS is premature.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="okr-structure-and-scoring">
      <p>OKRs combine a qualitative, inspiring Objective with 3–5 quantitative Key Results that prove the Objective was reached. The Objective answers "what we want to achieve"; the Key Results answer "how we will know we achieved it".</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Limit to 3–5 Objectives per period, each with 3–5 Key Results. Exceeding this produces a priority list, not a focus mechanism.</statement>
        <rationale>OKRs work through focus. More than 5 Objectives means everything is equally important, which means nothing is actually prioritised.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Objective Characteristics:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Objectives must be inspiring, qualitative, time-bound, ambitious, and memorable. If the Objective contains a number, it is a Key Result, not an Objective.</statement>
        <rationale>Numbers belong in Key Results. An Objective with a number ("increase signups by 20%") conflates aspiration with measurement and removes room for strategic flexibility.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Good Objective: "Delight our early adopters"—inspiring, qualitative, clear period</item>
        <item>Good Objective: "Build world-class onboarding"—ambitious, memorable</item>
        <item>Bad: "Increase signups by 20%"—that is a Key Result</item>
        <item>Bad: "Launch feature X"—that is a task</item>
        <item>Bad: "Improve stuff"—not testable, not inspiring</item>
      </list>

      <p>Key Result Characteristics:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Key Results must be measurable outcomes (not tasks or outputs), specific, time-bound, and set at 70% confidence—challenging but achievable without heroics.</statement>
        <rationale>The 70% confidence bar is empirically calibrated. 100% targets are sand-bagged; 40% targets are unrealistic stretch goals that demoralise. 70% keeps teams in the productive tension zone.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Good KR: "Reduce churn from 5% to 3% by end of Q2"—measurable, specific, time-bound outcome</item>
        <item>Good KR: "NPS score of 50+ by EOQ"—clear number, no ambiguity</item>
        <item>Bad KR: "Publish 12 blog posts"—that is an output/task, not an outcome</item>
        <item>Bad KR: "Activation rate improvement"—no number, not measurable</item>
      </list>

      <p>Scoring Scale:</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Score Key Results 0.0–1.0 at period end. 0.0–0.3 = failed, 0.4–0.6 = progress made, 0.7–1.0 = success. A 0.7 score is the ideal outcome—it means the target was a real stretch.</statement>
        <rationale>Consistently scoring 1.0 signals targets were too easy (sandbagging). Consistently scoring below 0.5 signals targets were unrealistic. The 0.7 calibration is a process health indicator.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="okr-setting-process">
      <p>Six-step process from strategy alignment through weekly tracking cadence.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1: Align to Strategy. Before drafting, gather: company mission/vision, annual goals, previous period retrospective findings, and current market conditions. Ask: "What must we accomplish this period to move toward our vision?"</statement>
        <rationale>OKRs disconnected from strategy are just metrics. The upward connection is what makes them directional rather than operational.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2: Draft Objectives. Brainstorm answers to three questions: "What is most important right now?", "If we could only achieve one thing, what would it be?", "What would make this quarter a success?" Then cut to 3–5 Objectives maximum.</statement>
        <rationale>Starting from one-thing thinking forces prioritisation before phrasing. This prevents the common failure of treating every theme as equally urgent.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3: Define Key Results. For each Objective, answer three questions: "How will we know we achieved it?", "What metrics matter?", "What is the target number?" Test: can you answer with just a number at the end of the period?</statement>
        <rationale>If you cannot answer with a single number, the KR is still a task or a vague aspiration. The number test is the falsifiability test.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4: Validate. Run four checks before publishing: Objectives are inspiring and qualitative, KRs are measurable outcomes not tasks, 70% confidence on each KR, all connect to higher-level goals, total count respects the limit.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping validation produces OKRs that look correct but fail in practice. The most common failure is KRs that are tasks dressed up with numbers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5: Communicate and Commit. Share OKRs with all stakeholders, get explicit buy-in, and make them visible—dashboard, wiki, or team channel. Visibility without commitment produces OKRs that are set and forgotten.</statement>
        <rationale>OKRs only work as coordination tools when everyone knows and accepts them. Private OKRs are just private goals.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6: Track and Adjust. Run weekly check-ins with progress percentage and confidence level per KR. Score monthly. Hold an end-of-period retrospective focused on accuracy, not just achievement.</statement>
        <rationale>Weekly check-ins surface blockers early. Monthly scoring maintains accountability without micromanagement. Retrospective on accuracy (not just score) improves the OKR-setting process itself.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="okr-examples-and-antipatterns">
      <p>SaaS product and solo creator OKR sets with full O/KR structure, and concrete antipatterns.</p>

      <p>SaaS Product OKRs:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Example: SaaS Product OKRs">
        <note>O1: Achieve product-market fit. KR1: increase "very disappointed" survey response from 25% to 40%. KR2: improve Day-30 retention from 20% to 35%. KR3: reach 100 paying customers with less than 10% monthly churn.</note>
        <note>O2: Build scalable acquisition engine. KR1: achieve 5,000 monthly organic visitors. KR2: reduce CAC from $200 to $100. KR3: maintain content pipeline of 12 blog posts published.</note>
        <note>O3: Delight early adopters. KR1: NPS score of 50+. KR2: average support response time under 4 hours. KR3: 10 customer testimonials collected.</note>
      </example>

      <p>Solo Creator OKRs:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Example: Solo Creator OKRs">
        <note>O1: Establish newsletter as primary channel. KR1: grow subscriber list from 500 to 2,000. KR2: maintain 45%+ open rate. KR3: convert 50 subscribers to paid product.</note>
        <note>O2: Launch first digital product. KR1: complete and launch course by [date]. KR2: generate $5,000 in first month. KR3: achieve 4.5+ star rating from first 20 customers.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Key Results that are tasks: "Publish 12 blog posts", "Launch feature X", "Run 5 user interviews".</description>
        <reason>Tasks measure output, not outcome. Completing the task does not prove the Objective was reached. Rewrite as the outcome the task enables: "Achieve 5,000 monthly organic visitors" instead of "Publish 12 blog posts".</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Too many OKRs: 7+ Objectives, each with 5 KRs.</description>
        <reason>Exceeding the 3–5 Objective cap destroys focus. With 7 Objectives, none gets the sustained attention needed to move metrics. Everything is equally urgent means nothing is actually prioritised.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Setting 100% confidence targets to guarantee achievement.</description>
        <reason>Sandbagged targets are not OKRs—they are delivery commitments with extra branding. A 100% score every quarter signals that targets need recalibration upward, not celebration.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Setting OKRs at the start of the quarter and not reviewing until the end.</description>
        <reason>Blocked KRs stay blocked without weekly visibility. Weekly check-ins catch blockers at week 3, not week 12.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No baseline for Key Results.</description>
        <reason>A KR without a starting point is unmeasurable. "NPS of 50+" without knowing current NPS cannot be scored. Always establish the baseline before setting the target.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/okr-doc.md" purpose="Quarterly OKR document with per-objective KR table, owner, status, and summary scorecard"/>
      <template path="templates/weekly-checkin.md" purpose="Weekly OKR check-in: progress by objective, blockers, help needed, weekly actions"/>
    </templates>

